# Coronary Arteries

> The coronary arteries are the **first branches of the [[Aorta]]**, arising just above the aortic valve cusps in the aortic sinuses (of Valsalva). They supply the [[Heart]] muscle (myocardium) with oxygenated blood during diastole.

## 🔗 Key Connections
- Arise from: [[Aorta]] (aortic sinuses)
- Supply: [[Heart]] (myocardium)

## 🗂️ Two Main Coronary Arteries

### Left Coronary Artery (LCA)
Arises from the left aortic sinus → short **left main** stem → divides into:

| Branch | Territory | Supplies |
|--------|-----------|---------|
| **Left Anterior Descending (LAD)** | Anterior | Anterior LV wall, anterior 2/3 of interventricular septum, anterior RV, apex |
| **Left Circumflex (LCx)** | Lateral/posterior | Lateral & posterior LV wall, left atrium; gives off obtuse marginal branches |

### Right Coronary Artery (RCA)
Arises from the right aortic sinus → travels in right AV groove:

| Branch | Territory | Supplies |
|--------|-----------|---------|
| **RCA main** | Right heart | Right atrium, RV anterior wall |
| **SA node artery** | SA node | 55% from RCA; 45% from LCx |
| **AV node artery** | AV node | 85% from RCA (dominant) |
| **Posterior Descending Artery (PDA)** | Posterior | Posterior 1/3 of septum, posterior LV/RV walls |

## 🔑 Coronary Dominance
- **Right dominant** (85%) — RCA gives rise to PDA
- **Left dominant** (8%) — LCx gives rise to PDA
- **Co-dominant** (7%) — both contribute

## 🔑 Venous Drainage
- **Great cardiac vein** → **coronary sinus** → right atrium (alongside LCA/LAD territory)
- **Middle cardiac vein** → coronary sinus (alongside PDA)
- **Small cardiac vein** → coronary sinus (alongside RCA)
- **Anterior cardiac veins** → drain directly into right atrium

## 🏥 Clinical Significance
- **Coronary artery disease (CAD)** — atherosclerotic plaque → angina (stable or unstable) → MI
- **LAD occlusion** — "widow maker"; anterior STEMI; most dangerous; can cause LV failure + septal defects
- **RCA occlusion** — inferior STEMI (II, III, aVF on ECG); AV block (AV node ischemia); RV infarction
- **LCx occlusion** — lateral STEMI (I, aVL, V5–V6); often electrically silent
- **STEMI territories on ECG**:
  - V1–V4 = anterior (LAD)
  - II, III, aVF = inferior (RCA)
  - I, aVL, V5–V6 = lateral (LCx)
  - V1–V2 = posterior (RCA/LCx) — tall R waves
- **Percutaneous coronary intervention (PCI)** — balloon angioplasty ± stent; treatment for STEMI
- **CABG (coronary artery bypass graft)** — internal mammary artery (IMA) used to bypass LAD (gold standard)


